# mood-tracker

A simple full-stack web application that allows users to log their daily mood and optional notes, store them in a MySQL database, and view recent mood entries.
This project demonstrates a complete workflow using React, Node.js/Express, MySQL, and deployment to a Linux VM with Nginx and PM2.

# Application Features

- Select a mood from predefined options

- Add optional notes

- Save mood entries to MySQL

- View a list of recent moods

- REST API with JSON responses

- Deployed and accessible via public IP

# Local Development Setup

- Clone the repository
- git clone https://github.com/<your-username>/mood-tracker.git
- cd mood-tracker

# Backend setup
- cd backend
- npm install




# Initialize the database:

node initDB.js

Start the backend:

npm start

Test backend:

http://localhost:3000/api/health

http://localhost:3000/api/moods

# Frontend setup (local)

- cd ../frontend
- npm install
- npm run dev


Frontend will call:

fetch('/api/moods')

# VM Deployment (Sprint 2)

System setup (Ubuntu VM)

sudo apt update
yes | sudo DEBIAN_FRONTEND=noninteractive apt-get -yqq upgrade


Install core dependencies:

sudo apt install -y git nginx mysql-server


Install Node.js (LTS) and PM2:

curl -fsSL https://deb.nodesource.com/setup_lts.x | sudo -E bash -
sudo apt install -y nodejs
sudo npm install -g pm2

# MySQL configuration

Create database and user:

CREATE DATABASE mood_tracker_db;
CREATE USER 'newuser'@'%' IDENTIFIED BY 'MoodPass321';
GRANT ALL PRIVILEGES ON mood_tracker_db.* TO 'newuser'@'%';
FLUSH PRIVILEGES;

# Backend deployment with PM2

cd /root
git clone https://github.com/<your-username>/mood-tracker.git
cd mood-tracker/backend
npm install
node initDB.js
pm2 start server.js --name mood-tracker
pm2 startup
pm2 save

# Frontend production build
cd ../frontend
npm install
npm run build


# Deploy frontend to Nginx:

sudo mkdir -p /var/www/mood-tracker
sudo rm -rf /var/www/mood-tracker/*
sudo cp -r dist/* /var/www/mood-tracker/

# Enable site 

sudo ln -s /etc/nginx/sites-available/mood-tracker /etc/nginx/sites-enabled/
sudo nginx -t
sudo systemctl reload nginx

# Accessing the app

http://164.92.87.138/
